Typedef Documentation

typedef void(* AlarmCallBackPtr)(uint32_t CbArg)

Alarm Callback Function pointer used in RTC001 App. The Alarm callback is called when an alarm event happens. For an alarm event to happen the compared value as well as the higher values should match and the user should have enabled alarm interrupt.

Parameters:
[in]CbArg

typedef enum RTC001_EnableType RTC001_EnableType

Inclusion of Header The RTC module needs to be enabled for the normal working. This is enumeration describes RTC001 App configuration.

typedef enum RTC001_ErrorType RTC001_ErrorType

This enumeration describes RTC001 App status types.

typedef enum RTC001_FlagType RTC001_FlagType

The Flags used in RTC includes the timer and the alarm flags. The flag types can be used to compare the status of flags in RTC as well as to clear the flags that are already set. This enumeration describes RTC001 App Flag status

typedef struct RTC001_HandleType RTC001_HandleType

This structure defines the RTC001 handle. The user selected clock, timer and divider values are used to fill this structure. The values are directly taken from the UI.

typedef struct RTC001_TimeHandle RTC001_TimeHandle

RTC001 Time Handle defining the structure for the values used in timer configuration.

typedef void(* RTC001_TimerCallBackPtr)(void *)

Timer Callback Function pointer used in RTC001 App. The Timer callback is called when a periodic timer event happens.

Definition at line 110 of file RTC001.h.

Function Documentation

void RTC001_Init ( void   )

Initialization function which initializes the App internal data structures to default values. The UI configurations are taken care in this function. The user entered values are taken into account while initialization. The RTC001_Clock_SetTime Api and RTC001_ConfigAlarm Api are called within the RTC001_Init function.

Returns:
void

Reentrant: NO

Example: 

  #include <DAVE3.h>
  int main(void)
  {
    // Initialize and RTC counter
    DAVE_Init(); // RTC001_Init() will be called within DAVE_Init()
    // ... infinite loop ...
    while(1)
    {}
  }
